node.text:
The 58m superyacht Illusion V has been designed as an ideal family charter vessel, sure to facilitate a good time for all who step onboard, both young and old. With ample space for relaxation including a private master suite, top deck Jacuzzi offering panoramic views, and multiple al fresco dining and lounge areas, Illusion V is the ultimate vessel for those looking to unwind. Though if you’re looking for a more active life at sea, Illusion V also offers an alfresco gym, a beach club and tender garage equipped with all of the latest toys, and an experienced crew ready to take you to the undiscovered gems of the Mediterranean and the Bahamas. The 2014-built Benetti superyacht Illusion V is available for charter through Camper & Nicholsons.
Video courtesy of @camperandnicholsons

node.text: With the 2021 Monaco Yacht Show just around the corner, Bluewater Yachts is delighted to announce that the 50m superyacht Mosaique will be available for private viewings. The Proteskan-built motor yacht received a newly painted hull and top sides in 2020 and has been regularly maintained since her launch in 2002. Mosaique’s interior was penned by Kristina Ferrand and accommodates 12 guests across six staterooms, including a full-beam master suite with a bathroom decorated in onyx and marble. Her upper deck is home to an alfresco dining area while a Jacuzzi, sunbeds and loungers are found on her sundeck. Mosaique is currently for sale and available for charter with Bluewater, who prides itself in being, “one company, one complete service.”

O’Pari’s magnificence is rooted much deeper than her 95m length and status as the largest superyacht in the Golden Yachts fleet. Delivered in 2020, the Studio Vafiadis-designed superyacht was meticulously built as a feature-rich charter-ready cruiser. With 12 luxurious staterooms, including two full-beam masters and a majority of VIPs, O’Pari accommodates up-to 24 guests who are in for the ultimate charter experience the moment they step onboard. From her massive swimming pool located on the bridge deck, to her outdoor cinema, and vast beach club and wellness area, the options to play or unwind at sea are infinite.
Video courtesy of @goldenyachts

The 72m superyacht Azteca, built by CRN in 2010 and refitted in 2021, is packed full with top-notch features across her four decks and more than 2,000 GT. From her opulent main saloon to her vast sun deck complete with a lounge area, an al fresco dining space, a Jacuzzi and aft deck, and a 100 square-metre beach club with a wealth of tenders and toys, Azteca, currently listed for sale, is ready to welcome aboard an owner looking to enjoy a life of luxury at sea.

node.text:
When looking to maximise space onboard with its 54m Nauta Wide superyacht concept, Nauta
Yachts opted to do something different. Mario Pedol, of Nauta Design explained, “Instead of focussing on length overall, we widened the beam to 11-metres and developed an innovative general arrangement.”
Designed for clients who want a superyacht spacious enough to accommodate a family in comfort, while still sized modestly enough to moor in the intimate bays and marinas of the Med. With ample deck space from her 100 square-metre beach club and massive sundeck, the Nauta 54m Wide combines high volume with a very elegant profile and has been designed to fully enjoy life at sea.

node.text: As one of the largest superyachts available to charter, the 136-metre Flying Fox is also, arguably, one of the most impressive. Built to the Lürssen pedigree and delivered in 2019, Flying Fox has it all. The 9,022 GT superyacht was designed by Espen Øino and offers as many as 25 guests onboard an unrivalled experience. With an infinite list of standout features – too many to list – some of the most worthy of a mention include her state-of-the-art diving centre, two helipads, 12-metre spa pool which runs transversely on the main deck, and her Mark Berryman-designed interior which includes a two-floor, 400 square-metre spa with a Cryo-Sauna onboard. Flying Fox is part of Imperial’s impressive fleet of charter yachts.

The 44.27-metre, sub-500 GT C144S is the latest from Polish shipyard Conrad Yachts. The superyacht features firm lines and a straight bow – where the ‘S’ in her name is derived — designed by Reymond Langton Design — while her naval architecture was completed by Diana Yacht Design. The interior of the semi-custom superyacht was penned by m2atelier and accommodates up-to 10 guests across five staterooms. Construction of the first unit is well underway, with an expected delivery to her Swiss owner in May 2022. A second unit of the series is currently in-build, with her keel laid this past December.
Images from @conradshipyard

node.text:
Veering away from the conventions of traditional yacht design led Sanlorenzo to discover an alternative layout that optimises the utilisation of interior spaces and the connection of life onboard to the sea. This was achieved by opting for an asymmetrical design, the namesake feature of the 37m SL120 Asymmetric. This series, of which two are already on the water and another five are currently in-build, eliminates the starboard side deck in order to maximise interior living space through the addition of a dining room to starboard and a living area that opens onto a balcony to port. In addition to this central feature, the SL120A has ample deck space including a large beach club situated on the lower deck aft, which opens from three sides to further emphasise the connection to the sea.
Video courtesy of @sanlorenzoyacht
